// ============================================================
// Block B6 — Admin: AI cost dashboard + RBAC user management
// (PATH-B FRAGMENT, NOT YET MERGED)
// ============================================================
//
// SCOPE FOR B6:
//   The cost dashboard reads from the existing AuditLog rows that the AI
//   services already write — `ai.question.generate`, `openai.image.generate`,
//   `ai.quick_paper.generate`, `svg.diagram.generate` — and aggregates on
//   the fly. No new tables are required for cost tracking.
//
//   The RBAC controller manages the existing `User` model. To support the
//   "deactivate user" feature we need a single new boolean column on User.
//
// REQUIRED CHANGES on the existing User model in `schema.prisma`
// (the integrator must add these — B6 cannot touch schema.prisma):
//
//     model User {
//       …existing fields…
//       isActive     Boolean   @default(true)   // <-- ADD THIS
//     }
//
//   Once that column exists:
//   - AuthService.login should reject a login when user.isActive === false
//     (returns the same generic 401 to avoid user-enumeration leak).
//     This is documented in MERGE_INSTRUCTIONS.md and is a follow-up task
//     for the auth owner — B6 cannot edit auth/.
//   - AdminRbacService.update writes to this column.
//
// NOTE — B6 does NOT add new tables. The dashboard endpoints aggregate
// AuditLog (`metadata.costUsd`) at request time. If aggregation cost
// becomes a problem at scale, a future block can introduce a daily-rollup
// materialised table; the API surface is the same so the FE doesn't need
// to change.
//
// Until the schema migration lands, the deactivate path falls back to a
// soft "deactivation" by setting passwordHash to an unusable sentinel
// (`!DEACTIVATED!:<originalHash>`) so logins fail. This is implemented
// in AdminRbacService.update behind a feature flag detected at runtime
// (a Prisma error means the column doesn't exist yet) — see service code.
